player.seasonOutlook: Davis was arguably the top producer in the league last season before his trade request to the Lakers was made public and his season subsequently went downhill. He is 26 years old, in the midst of what should be his peak seasons, and he will be playing next to one of the elite players and playmakers in the NBA in LeBron James. Davis should face less defensive attention and be put in better positions to score, improving his percentages with only James capping his volume upside.

Leonard turned the basketball world upside down this offseason when he joined the Clippers and brought Paul George with him. He missed 22 games last season for maintenance purposes, and with the Clippers boasting deep talent and George as well, Leonard could still get plenty of rest again this season. He should have excellent per-game stats, if a bit attenuated due to his strong teammates, but the maintenance games could drop him slightly in the rankings.

Walker replaces Kyrie Irving as the high-volume lead guard on the Celtics but presumably will take a step back usage-wise with his stronger supporting cast in Boston. His scoring and 3-point volume likely decrease, but his efficiency and assists could potentially take upticks in his new role.

Russell established himself as an NBA All-Star with the Nets last season, and now makes the big transition to more of an off-ball role with the Warriors this season. Russell will become at best a tertiary offensive creator behind Stephen Curry and Draymond Green, but he will play most of the season in the Klay Thompson (ACL) role which should produce lots of 3-pointers and scoring opportunities for a Warriors squad that will need the points.

Love missed 60 games last season and 105 games during the past three seasons as injuries have taken a major toll. The Cavaliers are in full rebuild mode, which doesn't seem to fit with a 30-something All-Star like Love. If he remains with the team and healthy, Love still has 20-10 upside with strong 3-point volume from a big man.

Bledsoe is established in his role as the third scorer and secondary playmaker for the Bucks, and if his free throw percentage bounces back into the 80% range after an eight-year low of 75% last season, Bledsoe would be a strong across-the-board contributor with very little downside this season.

Gallinari missed only 14 games last season, the fewest he's missed since the 2011-12 season. He also turned in career highs with 19.8 PPG, 6.1 RPG, 2.4 3PG and 46.3 FG%. This offseason, he moved from a deep Clippers squad to a depleted Thunder team, where he projects as the featured scorer. He could put up top-30 value in fantasy drafts, but the specter of injury likely slides him into the early-middle rounds.

Jordan is exactly who he is at this point of his career, with per-possession averages that have stayed rock steady over the past five seasons, whether he was playing with the Clippers, Mavericks or Knicks. We thus know what to expect from him per minute in Brooklyn, with the only question being how the minutes are split between Jordan and Jarrett Allen. His ceiling is a bit lower due to the time split, although there were wild rumors that he and Allen were working on 3-point shots during the offseason in hopes of playing together.

Richardson is coming off the best season of his career, during which he set  personal records across the board as "the man" for the Heat. This season, he will play more of a secondary role for the 76ers, which caps his scoring and assist volume but could lead to better shooting percentages, more 3-pointers and better defensive stats. That might make him more valuable in roto than points leagues.

Winslow expanded his game last season when he started for extended periods at point guard, a skill set that could make him valuable as a secondary ball handler and defensive forward while playing off of Jimmy Butler. Winslow projects as a solid all-around threat with more than a 3-pointer and steal per game.

Isaac was drafted sixth overall in 2017 as an athletic development prospect, and last season, he continued to develop and started 64 games. This season, he projects as a double-digit scorer with solid rebounding and could average more than one block, steal and 3-pointer per game. This gives him expected value near the top 100 of roto leagues with upside to flirt with the top 50 if he makes a significant, but achievable, third-year jump.

Thomas finished top-5 in the NBA MVP race just three seasons ago, but he was essentially out of the league last season as he continued to recover from hip surgery. This campaign, he will battle Ish Smith for minutes at the Wizards� point with John Wall out. If healthy, Thomas has the opportunity to win the job, though he currently projects as the backup. Health is by far the biggest question mark with him this season and moving forward.
Currently unsigned, but REALLY wishes that he were signed.

Tucker embraced a larger role for the Rockets last season, playing 34.2 MPG in 82 games. His noteworthy contributions were reflected in 1.8 3PG and 1.6 SPG, with 5.8 RPG as a third category of interest. He is a real-life defensive specialist, so he is unlikely to produce the volume to be valuable in points leagues, but that unique combo of steals and 3-pointers could generate some interest late in roto drafts.
